Tier 1 — Blockers (resolve before BRD sign-off)
Q1. Does the solution write back to settlement systems, or doesn't it?
§7.8 and UC-10 say the solution "writes the cashflow status back to NEWS / settlement system under the analyst's identity." §9.3.1(iii) says the opposite: the UI "shall present cashflow outcomes up to Matched or Unmatched step and further action will be taken by analyst as per his current workflow," with post-trade controls operating "outside the new solution." UC-10 then muddles it further: "this step is done manually by analyst." These cannot all be true. This single answer decides the integration surface, the InfoSec posture, and roughly half the claimed time saving. It is the highest-value question in the document.

Q2. Is the Work Driver Onboarding Wizard the same build as this pilot, or a different one?
A complete second BRD (its own §2–§12, its own UC-1–UC-9) is embedded between §7 and §8. It states the platform "is being proven first on the Allege work driver (OTC Derivatives)." If the OTC pilot runs on the Wizard, then every OTC requirement should be expressed as a wizard configuration, and the hard-coded Tier 1/2/3 cascade, per-product thresholds and PCM-specific logic in §7.7 are architecturally wrong. If it's a separate platform, this section doesn't belong here. Right now two different target architectures are being signed off in one document.

Q3. Under 100% human-in-the-loop, which of the eight as-is steps actually disappear?
§5.4 lists eight analyst steps. Phase 1 retains: allocation (Step 1), reading the email to confirm extraction (Step 2), reviewing the match (Steps 4–5), all unmatched investigation (Step 6), manual Outlook replies (Step 7, per §4.2(a)), and — if Q1 resolves toward §9.3.1(iii) — the PCM update (Step 8). That leaves Step 3 (locate the trade) and part of Step 2 as the only genuine eliminations. Please provide the step-level time breakdown of the 10–20 minutes that underpins the reduction target. Without it the target is unfalsifiable.

Q4. What is the actual addressable volume, in absolute numbers, and what is the team headcount?
§5.6 gives only ratios: 32% of the mailbox is from counterparties; 45% of "external mails" are fresh. That implies Phase 1 addresses roughly 14% of mailbox volume — and less once you remove SSI/Reaffirmation-labelled mail, PDF attachments, .msg, and password-protected files. Also: is "external mails" the same population as the 32%, or a different denominator? The document never states absolute daily volume or how many analysts are on the team. Without both, you cannot size the benefit, size Chinou capacity (dependency §4.4(d)), or set any SLA.

Q5. Does Phase 1 need NEWS integration at all?
§5.3 Flow B is explicit that counterparty-initiated new emails "do not pass through NEWS at all and arrive directly into Outlook." Phase 1 scope is Theme 2.1 and 3.1 — both Flow B. So for in-scope mail there is no originating NEWS work item to write back to. Yet §4.4(a) makes NEWS integration the scope-critical dependency and §7.8 routes write-back through it. If Phase 1 only needs PCM, you can remove your highest-risk dependency from the critical path. If it does need NEWS, explain how a NEWS record gets created for an email NEWS never issued.

Q6. All eleven access requests are Open. What is the drop-dead date, and has anyone confirmed NEWS has a programmatic interface?
§4.4 states that if these dependencies don't hold, "scope is materially affected." §15.C shows every row as Open, including PCM read and NEWS. §4.4(a) hedges that NEWS may not be integrable at all — has this been confirmed with Punya M / Santosh J? A BRD cannot be signed off against a dependency that has been identified but never tested.

Q7. The rule that defines Phase 1 scope is deferred to build.
§7.3 leaves the "newly-initiated thread" detection rule "to be finalised during build phase." That rule is the in/out boundary for the entire pilot — it decides Theme 2/3 (in) versus Theme 1 (out). It is a requirement, not an implementation detail. Relatedly, §6.5 says the counterparty-initiates-new-email-but-references-a-NEWS-thread case "can be skipped from the pilot" — skipped meaning dropped silently, or tagged for the analyst? Silent drops on a settlement workflow will not pass audit.

Q8. Is the 4-eye threshold $5M or $500K?
§5.8, §4.2(l), §7.8 and §7.11 all say $5mil. UC-10 says "(e.g., $500K)" and the Glossary says "(e.g., >$500K)". That is a 10x discrepancy on an existing post-trade control, in a document that promises Compliance the control is "preserved without modification." Compliance will find this.

Q9. The Tier 2 tolerances are either wrong or undefined, and the worked example doesn't compute.
Three problems in §7.7. First, "notional ± 50$ equivalent" on OTC notionals of ~$50M is a tolerance of 0.0001% — functionally an exact match, so Tier 2 will never fire on notional. Was this meant to be ±$50K, or ±50bps? Second, "value date ±Z business days" — Z is never defined anywhere in the document. Third, I checked the worked example against a calendar: it calls 5 May 2026 a Monday (it is a Tuesday) and gives the upper bound as 9 May, which is a Saturday — excluded by the document's own business-day rule. With 6 and 7 May as holidays, ±2 business days from 5 May is 1 May to 11 May, not "1st May to 9th May." Also: what is the FX source for "$ equivalent" when the notional is in JPY?

Q10. The "Compare & Match Scenarios reference" is the scope baseline and is not attached.
It is cited about ten times as authoritative (Themes 1–4, sub-scenarios 1.1–1.4, 2.1, 3.1, 4.1–4.4) and Phase 1 scope is defined entirely by reference to it. It is not in §15 Appendices, has no version, and no link. Everything signed off here inherits its ambiguity.

Tier 2 — Material (resolve before FSD)
Matching engine
Q11. §7.7 defines "Tier 1, exact match" twice, with different logic — once as a counterparty-reference cascade, once as all-economic-fields-exact. Is the counterparty-reference search a separate tier or a sub-step?

Q12. UC-07 step 3 handles "multiple candidates returned" at Tier 1, but "multiple Tier 1 candidates" is absent from §7.7's list of outcomes presented to the analyst. Missing outcome type in the state model.

Q13. Tier 3 drops the counterparty filter entirely. On amount/CCY/VD/direction alone this could return very large candidate sets across the whole book — and surface other counterparties' trades to the analyst. What is the candidate cap, and is cross-counterparty visibility acceptable to Compliance?

Q14. §4.2(e) defers aggregation logic, so the matcher cannot detect an aggregate case — yet §7.7 lists "Aggregate-Match Scenario" as a distinct outcome presented to the analyst. Without aggregation logic these are simply unmatched. Delete the outcome, or fund the detection.

Q15. The netting requirement in §7.7 is an incomplete sentence: "In case of Netting in PCM, if only one leg is matched n other is not matched –". Please complete it. The following line ("the solution will work on each entry of the net") appears to say something different.

Q16. Is the counterparty resolved to a canonical code via Eve before matching, or is the raw email string matched against PCM? If the former, Tier 2's fuzzy name matching is redundant. This shapes the design.

Q17. §7.9 prioritises by trade value, highest first — but at the Awaiting-Confirmation stage the notional is an unconfirmed AI extraction. You'd be ranking the queue by a number nobody has checked. Also, multi-currency ranking needs an FX rate: which source, what base, struck when?

Extraction scope — three direct contradictions
Q18. Images in the email body: in or out? §4.1(b) supports "plain-text and HTML email body" only. §6.1(7) catalogues embedded images as a variation. UC-04 pre-condition says the body is parseable "as text or HTML or image." §13.5(iii) tests it. Three sections disagree.

Q19. Password-protected attachments: in or out? §6.2(3) says out of scope. UC-05 pre-condition says "Attachment is .xls or .xlsx and may or may not be password-protected." Direct contradiction.

Q20. What does "mandatory for extraction" mean? §7.5 marks six fields mandatory, but only says low-confidence flags "rather than blocking the workflow." If a counterparty email omits the Nomura entity name — common in free-form mail — does the record block, or reach the analyst incomplete? And is "Nomura entity name" realistically present in counterparty correspondence? Worth an SME check.

Q21. Why is SSI mandatory to extract when it is never used? §7.5 makes SSI (bank name/BIC, account, beneficiary, intermediary) mandatory. §4.2(f) defers SSI handling; SSI-labelled mail isn't advanced; and SSI appears in none of the Tier 1/2/3 match field lists. You are mandating extraction of the most sensitive data in the email for no consumer.

Q22. Is multilingual handling actually in Phase 1? §6.4 requires German/Japanese and mixed-language "without loss of fidelity" — a hard requirement — yet there is no accuracy target per language, no volume estimate, and no confirmation Chinou supports it. Either scope it with evidence or move it to Phase 2.

State model & tagging
Q23. There are two incompatible tag taxonomies. §7.4 defines four tags (Awaiting Confirmation, Awaiting review, Resolved-Matched, Resolved-Unmatched). UC-03 uses a different set ("Picked – Queued for Extraction", "Picked – Awaiting Analyst Action"). Which is real?

Q24. There is no failure tag. §9.2.10 says a failed email "remains in the analyst's queue" — but the taxonomy has no exception state, so a failed extraction stays tagged Awaiting Confirmation indefinitely.

Q25. "Resolved-Unmatched" is not resolved. §7.4 defines it as "analyst working on this case manually now," while §7.9's Resolved bucket means "action is complete" and UC-12 says unmatched items stay in Open/Critical until resolution. So the Outlook tag says Resolved while the GUI says Open. Please supply a single state machine covering both surfaces.

Q26. Reassignment is missing. §7.4 says the assigned-analyst tag "does not change as the email moves through processing states." What happens when the analyst is on leave, or the queue needs rebalancing?

Q27. Is the Outlook tag an Outlook Category? If so, a taxonomy of <analyst-id>,<stage> produces analysts × 4 combinations against a shared mailbox's category master list, which has practical limits. Worth a technical feasibility check before the FSD assumes it.

Roles, config ownership and segregation of duties
Q28. Who owns thresholds — AI CoE or Settlements Ops? §11.3: "Threshold configuration shall be owned by Settlements Operations leadership." §12.2 RACI: Accountable = AI Center of Excellence. Pick one.

Q29. Who owns counterparty→analyst mapping — Manager or Admin? §9.3.2 assigns it to the Manager row and lists an "analysts-client allocation panel" under Admin. UC-14 says Manager is read-only and cannot change admin-controlled settings.

Q30. Which allocation rule is it? §5.3 says alphabet-wise; §5.3 also says "as per client allocation model"; §5.4 Step 1 says "agreed client allocation list"; §7.4 says "existing alphabet-wise mapping"; §9.3.2 says counterparty-to-analyst mapping. These are described as at least two different rules.

Q31. §9.3.2 says "a user has one role per session," but §5.3 says AMs and above do allocation — meaning a real person needs both Manager and Analyst capability. How does an AM who also works a queue operate?

Q32. §7.2.1 gives routing control to "Settlements Operations leadership" via the admin interface. The team that owns the benefit metric would then control the routing percentage and the AI thresholds. Is that segregation of duties acceptable to Compliance?

Q33. The AI CoE holds authority to disable/rollback (§12.5(iv)) and is Accountable in the RACI — but appears in neither the stakeholder table (§3.2) nor the distribution list. Same for InfoSec, which holds a pre-deployment sign-off gate (§10.2).

AI governance & data
Q34. Are the confidence scores real? The entire threshold framework (§11) assumes every AI recommendation "carries a confidence score," and §11.4 asks you to measure "confidence calibration." If Chinou returns a self-reported LLM confidence rather than token-level logprobs, these numbers are not calibrated and the thresholds are decorative. This is a business-visible control, not a technical footnote.

Q35. Does Chinou pin model versions? §12.4 requires change control over "model version." If Chinou upgrades the underlying model beneath you, that is an uncontrolled change to a validated system — and it will invalidate your golden-dataset evaluation without anyone raising a change request.

Q36. "Retraining" language doesn't match the design. §13.1 says models are "configured via prompt engineering and few-shot examples" — no fine-tuning. But §11.5 and §13.4 discuss "retraining signals" and flagging "a model for review." With a prompt-only design, the lever is prompt iteration. Align the terminology or the Compliance reviewer will assume a training pipeline exists.

Q37. The golden dataset has a point-in-time problem. §13.1 requires "expected match outcome per trade across Tier 1, Tier 2, and Tier 3" — but match outcomes depend on PCM state at that moment. Historical emails replayed against today's PCM will produce different answers, since those trades have since settled. Do you need a point-in-time PCM snapshot? This is a real engineering cost that isn't in the roadmap.

Q38. Redaction may destroy the dataset. §13.1 says "redaction shall be applied where necessary before use in lower environments." Counterparty names and SSI details are the signal being extracted and matched. Who decides what's redacted, and how do you validate extraction on redacted data?

Q39. The audit store will hold unredacted SSI. §12.3(iii) captures "input passed to the model (email content)" for every inference. That duplicates full counterparty correspondence — including bank account numbers — into a new store. §9.4 defers to "Nomura's existing retention framework" without stating the actual period. What are the encryption, access and retention requirements for that store?

Q40. Data residency is unaddressed. §5.5 is headed "Systems involved today in SSG," implying an India-based team; counterparties may be EU or Japanese. Counterparty email content flowing to Chinou raises residency and possibly GDPR/APPI questions. §10.2 requires InfoSec sign-off on residency but the BRD states no position for InfoSec to sign off on.

Q41. Vendor risk is absent. §3.2 lists a "Vendor Team" and §14.2 says build is by an "external delivery team." A third party building an AI system that touches settlement data and counterparty SSIs needs a TPRM position: who are they, do they get production email access, do they get the golden dataset?

Operational controls
Q42. Deduplication is deferred — but write-back is not. §9.2.2 defers dedup to Phase 2, while §6.8 confirms duplicate sends are real. If a duplicate email creates a second work item that an analyst independently confirms, can the same cashflow be released twice? What is the compensating control? Also, §9.2.2 says dedup will be taken up "with learning from phase1" — but you cannot learn about duplicates you never detect. What measurement in Phase 1 informs that decision?

Q43. There is no reversal path. If an analyst confirms a match, write-back fires, and it's later found wrong — how is it unwound? The as-is SIPOC includes "amend, cancel-rebook." No requirement covers correction of a solution-triggered write-back.

Q44. OOO, bounce-backs and marketing mail add work rather than remove it. §7.3 assumes these are "low-volume and will surface as exceptions at the extraction step" — meaning the analyst gets an exception for every newsletter. §13.5(v) tests for it adversarially. What evidence supports "low-volume," and shouldn't there be an explicit requirement?

Q45. The Eve allowlist should drive the structural filter. The Glossary describes Eve as holding a "counterparty / broker email allowlist," yet §7.3's structural filter only drops @nomura.com. Allowlisting known counterparty domains would resolve Q44 directly. Note the response to margin comment [RH46] points to §6.3 — but §6.3 is a catalogue of variations, not a requirement. That comment is not actually closed.

Q46. §6.3's broker bullet is self-contradictory. It says a broker/intermediary email "maps unambiguously to a known counterparty in Nomura's master" — identical wording to the direct-counterparty bullet above it. A broker's domain maps to the broker, not the underlying client. This looks like a copy-paste error, and it matters because FR §9.2.5 keys off exactly this judgement.

Q47. Ageing is used everywhere and defined nowhere. It drives the Critical bucket (§7.9), secondary sort, an Admin config item, a success metric, and SIPOC's T+0/T+1/T+2+ buckets. From what clock — email receipt, or value date? Relatedly, §9.2.7 defines Critical as "marked critical in Eve/Takara" while §7.9 defines it as Matched-but-Settled, low-confidence-on-high-value, and ageing. Two definitions.

Q48. Latency and hours are undefined. §9.5.1 promises availability "during the operational hours of the OTC Settlements team" without naming them or the region. §9.5 promises processing "within agreed time targets" that are never agreed. Given VD-2 driven cashflows, is a 60-minute pilot poll acceptable near cut-off?

Q49. Routing control mechanics. Is the percentage applied per email at random, per counterparty, or per analyst? Random-per-email gives every analyst a split workflow across two surfaces, which may increase handling time during dual-running. And on emergency rollback to 0%, what happens to items already in flight? §11.3 protects in-flight items from threshold changes but says nothing about routing.

Q50. Shadow mode needs ground truth that doesn't exist today. §13.3 compares solution output against the analyst's manual handling — but §5.7 identifies precisely that as a pain point: the manual outcome is scattered across Outlook, NEWS, PCM and analyst notes. Capturing comparable ground truth means analysts double-key during shadow mode. Who pays for that, and is it in the roadmap?

The prototype contradicts the BRD
Q51. §9.3.3's screens appear to be built against a different specification, and they're in the sign-off pack:

The data model treats Allege as an upstream entity ("Total Open Alleges", "Allege ID", "Allege status") — §7.7 and the Glossary insist there is no upstream Allege classifier and that Allege is only a match outcome. These are different data models.
Admin shows "62% Auto-Resolution Rate" — Phase 1 has explicitly zero auto-resolution (§9.3.4(e), §11.1).
Audit Trail shows "AI Acceptance Rate 7% / Override Rate 93%" — inverted against the <10% override target.
"5 SLA Breaches Today" — no SLA is defined anywhere (Q47/Q48).
Manager has a "Nudge" button — §9.3.2 says Manager is read-only and "cannot action." What is Nudge, and who receives it?
Login reads "ABC India FX Settlement" and the screens reference MT300 and "Approved SSI re-send" — but scope is OTC Derivatives, FX is excluded per §4.2(g), and SSI handling is deferred per §4.2(f).
"Confirmations Analyst" appears as a role; §9.3.2 has only Analyst/Manager/Admin, and §9.2.9 says "there is only analyst role but we would need analyst and manager roles" — omitting Admin, which §11.3 requires.
Tier 3 — Defects and document control (editorial pass)
These don't change the build, but several will be caught by Compliance or Audit and cost you a review cycle:

Garbled numbers in the success metrics table (§14.1): "5540% reduction" and "Less than 4-810%" look like unresolved tracked-change merges. What are the real targets?
STP metric is incoherent (§14.1): baseline 93% → target 97%, but the Glossary defines STP as settling "without manual intervention," and §5.2 says only 5–10% flows without analyst involvement. Phase 1 is 100% HITL, so in-scope STP is 0% by definition. Is this KRI measuring a different population?
A metric with no delta (§14.1): "cashflows escalated to analyst for manual update — Today: all; Phase 1 target: all." By design there is no improvement. Why is it a success metric?
Baseline conflict: §5.6 says 10–20 minutes per cashflow; §14.1 says 15–20.
Duplicate section numbering: §2, §3, §4, §7 each appear twice (OTC and Wizard). Two use-case ID schemes coexist (UC-1…UC-9 and UC-01…UC-15). This breaks traceability into the FSD.
Broken cross-references: §14.4(iii) cites "Section 15.1" for operational metrics (should be 14.1); §9.2.10 and §12.5(iii) cite "Section 9, Functional Requirement 1" for the routing percentage, which actually lives at §7.2.1 (FR 1 is the polling interval).
Scope Decision Log (§4.5) doesn't do its job: Sr. No 5 is missing; Decision Owner and Date are blank on every row; §4.2(k) and (l) are merged into "4.2(kl)", so "Modification of existing controls" has no entry of its own. Its stated purpose is to record rationale, owner and date — none are captured, in a document heading to Compliance.
Access Register (§15.C): rows 8 and 9 are missing. No row exists for Chinou API (despite dependency §4.4(d)), front-office systems (§5.5), or the currency-holiday feed — §7.7 cites a Thomas Murray login URL, which is not an integration. Is there an API or data feed?
Reference data naming is inconsistent: "Talara / Takara" (§15.C row 11), "Eve/Takara" (§9.2.7), "Eve/RDM" (§5.5), "Eve" elsewhere. Is Takara the bank-holiday source (§7.7) and the credit-risk system (§9.2.11)? Is Eve the counterparty master, a reference-data system, or an email allowlist? The Glossary and §5.5 say different things.
"ABC" appears where Nomura is meant (§1.1, §2.1, §4.2(h), and the prototype's "ABC India FX Settlement"). Redaction placeholder, or a real system name?
§11.2 references an "Allege-classified email" — residual language from a superseded design where an upstream Allege classifier existed.
§11.2's first row is a null control: below-threshold on email identification means "routed to extraction," which is also what above-threshold means for unlabelled mail. So low classifier confidence has no analyst-visible consequence, and an SSI email the classifier is unsure about silently enters the Allege flow — where SSI handling is out of scope. Should low-confidence identification flag to the analyst instead?
Exec summary says four capabilities; §7 says seven — and the summary's list omits analyst confirmation, which is the pilot's principal control.
§12.1 calls the operating model "suggestive" / "suggested." A BRD going for Compliance sign-off cannot propose its governance model tentatively.
§12.7 makes a model accountable: "accountability rests with the model and its governance owners." A model cannot hold accountability. Name the human role.
Document metadata: Version 0.2, dated May 2026, Status "Draft" — today is July 2026, and §14.1 still carries an open action ("Haris will review — comment on 26th May"). Is this current? Distribution list still shows Compliance and Internal Audit as TBC while §10.2 makes their sign-off a deployment gate.
Sign-off matrix is undefined: §3.2 marks both Sriram Iyer (Exec Sponsor) and Bipin Kadam (Business Owner) as "Accountable, sign-off"; §14.2's gate says "BRD signed off by Settlements Operations leadership"; §10.2 adds Compliance and InfoSec. Who actually signs, and in what order? Sriram Iyer isn't on the distribution list.
The two utilities are treated as one solution. §15.B registers two separate NTIs (TDG1001567/8) and two AI CoE use cases (AIUC00336/337) for the Unstructured-to-Structured and Compare & Match utilities. If they're separately deliverable and reusable — which §4.1's forward-extensibility argument depends on — they need their own interfaces and acceptance criteria.
Roadmap conflict: the Wizard's §12 puts "multi-source input (more than one input source per activity)" out of scope, but OTC Phase 2 (§4.3) requires mailbox + TRAM + shared folders for the same activity.
§14.2 has no dates and no 1a/1b sequencing decision. Are Phase 1a and 1b built in parallel or serially, and does 1a go live independently — implying an extra cut-over?
